    blocks: [
      { type: "h1", text: `[Title Page]\nDon’t Bet the Business\nHow Manufacturing Companies Test Strategic Ideas Before Investing Big Money\nBy [Your Name/Author Name]` },
      { type: "h1", text: `Introduction\nThe Costly Decision Trap` },
      { type: "p", text: `Walk onto the shop floor of almost any mid-sized manufacturing company that has been operating for more than a decade, and if you look closely enough, you will find it.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Usually, it is sitting in the back corner of the facility, pushed up against a wall, draped in a dusty plastic tarp, or quietly being used as an incredibly expensive table to store empty cardboard boxes.` },
      { type: "p", text: `It is the physical monument to a failed strategic bet.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Perhaps it is a specialized ₹3 Crore multi-axis tube laser. Perhaps it is an automated powder-coating line. Or maybe it is an entire climate-controlled cleanroom that hasn't seen a human being in eighteen months.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Whenever I see one of these silent, idle monuments on a factory floor, I ask the founder the exact same question: "What is the story behind that machine?"` },
      { type: "p", text: `The founder will usually sigh, look at the floor, and tell a story that goes exactly like this:` },
      { type: "p", text: `Two years ago, the leadership team identified a massive, highly promising market opportunity. Maybe it was a sudden boom in electric vehicle (EV) components. Maybe it was a government mandate pushing for localized defense manufacturing. Or maybe it was a lucrative export opportunity to European buyers who were looking for a "China Plus One" supplier.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The boardroom buzzed with excitement. The spreadsheets were drawn up. The return on investment (ROI) looked absolutely spectacular on paper.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Because the opportunity was so "obvious," and because the leadership team was terrified that their competitors would beat them to the punch, they decided to move with aggressive speed. They called the bank. They took out a massive term loan. They signed a purchase order for the specialized machinery. They leased an extra 5,000 square feet of floor space. They hired a new production manager and spent a fortune flying the sales team to trade shows in Germany.` },
      { type: "p", text: `They bet the business on the opportunity.` },
      { type: "p", text: `And then... nothing happened.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Two years later, the promised demand never materialized. The European buyers stopped returning emails. The defense contracts were delayed by bureaucracy. The EV market shifted its design parameters, rendering the newly purchased machines obsolete.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Now, the company is saddled with a crippling monthly EMI payment for a machine that produces zero revenue. The CFO is panicking about cash flow. The sales team is demoralized. And the business is suddenly vulnerable to bankruptcy, all because they confused a strategic idea with a strategic certainty.` },
      
      { type: "figure", title: "Illustration 1: The Monument to Bad Strategy", visual: "A stark, black-and-white illustration of a massive, expensive piece of industrial machinery sitting in a dark corner of a factory, completely covered by a dusty plastic tarp.", caption: "The physical cost of an untested assumption." },

      { type: "h2", text: `The Illusion of the Bold Leap` },
      { type: "p", text: `There is a toxic myth in the business world, perpetuated by magazines, motivational speakers, and startup culture. It is the myth of the "Bold Leap."` },
      { type: "p", text: `We are taught that great entrepreneurs are gamblers. We are told that to achieve massive growth, a founder must trust their gut, burn the boats, and push all their chips into the center of the table.` },
      { type: "p", text: `In the software industry, betting the business is relatively cheap. If a software company builds a bad app, they lose a few months of programmer salaries. They can rewrite the code over the weekend and try again.` },
      { type: "p", text: `But in the heavy industrial manufacturing sector, betting the business requires concrete, steel, high-voltage electricity, and multi-million-rupee capital expenditure. When a manufacturer makes a bad bet, they cannot just "pivot" over the weekend. They are stuck with three tons of useless iron bolted to their factory floor.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The core insight of this book is simple, but it will fundamentally change how you deploy capital for the rest of your career:` },
      { type: "quote", text: `Many companies make massive strategic bets based on hope, disguised as strategy.\nSmart companies do not operate on hope. Smart companies test their strategic ideas to generate prospective data before they commit serious capital.` },
      { type: "h2", text: `The Paradigm Shift: From "Evidence" to "Prospective Data"` },
      { type: "p", text: `When a leadership team debates a new strategic direction—like shifting from commercial components to aerospace—the accountants and engineers in the room will naturally demand "evidence" that the market exists.` },
      { type: "p", text: `But demanding "evidence" is a linguistic trap. Evidence, by definition, is a record of the past. If you are launching a completely new strategic advantage that your company has never offered before, there is no past evidence to look at. If you wait until an opportunity is so heavily documented and proven that it is generating historical evidence, the market is already saturated. You are too late.` },
      { type: "p", text: `You cannot use past evidence to prove a future strategy.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Instead, you must build confidence through prospective data.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Prospective data is the information you actively generate today to de-risk your decisions about tomorrow. It is the signal you extract from the market by running small, cheap, rapid experiments.` },
      { type: "p", text: `If you think European buyers will pay a 20% premium for your new rapid-prototyping capability, you do not buy the machines and wait to see if you were right. You design a low-cost experiment to see if a buyer will sign a Letter of Intent before the machines even exist. You generate prospective data.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The goal of this book is to teach you how to stop gambling. You will learn how to take the brilliant strategic choices you made in the boardroom and slice them into tiny, testable assumptions.` },
      { type: "p", text: `You will learn how to generate the prospective data required to build absolute, unshakable confidence in your strategy. And most importantly, you will learn how to protect your balance sheet from the devastating cost of a bad gut feeling.` }
    ]
