  {
    id: "ch9",
    title: "Chapter 9: When to Commit Capital",
    type: "chapter",
    blocks: [
      { type: "h1", text: `Chapter 9\nWhen to Commit Capital` },
      { type: "p", text: `The atmosphere in your boardroom has fundamentally changed.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Thirty days ago, the room was divided. The Faction of Hope was arguing with the Faction of Fear over a massive, multi-million-rupee strategic pivot. The whiteboard was covered in terrifying, untested assumptions.` },
      { type: "p", text: `But you did not succumb to the Capital Trap. You did not blindly sign a bank loan based on a "gut feeling." You forced your team to act like scientists. You isolated the Deal Killers. You designed a Thin-Slice experiment, or you built a highly realistic Fake Door.` },
      { type: "p", text: `And now, the results are in.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The corporate buyer did not give you a polite deflection. They did not ask for a massive discount. They signed the Letter of Intent (LOI). They paid the premium on the RFQ Stress Test. They accepted the Ugly Duckling prototype and officially specified your new design into their engineering blueprints.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The Deal Killer assumption has been definitively neutralized. Your hypothesis is validated. You have generated undeniable, mathematical prospective data.` },
      { type: "p", text: `At this exact moment, your role as the CEO shifts dramatically. You must stop acting like a paranoid scientist, and you must start acting like an aggressive, uncompromising industrialist.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Testing is a tool for learning, but testing does not scale. You cannot run a ₹50 Crore manufacturing business using manual hacks, outsourced proxies, and Ugly Ducklings forever. To capture the massive profit margins waiting in your new strategic arena, you must transition from the Cost of Learning back to the Cost of Production.` },
      { type: "p", text: `You must commit the capital.` },

      { type: "h2", text: `Micro-Teardown: The Three Pillars of Capital Readiness` },
      { type: "p", text: `Founders often struggle with the transition from testing to execution. Because the testing phase was so cheap and safe, the sudden prospect of signing a ₹5 Crore equipment loan still feels terrifying, even with the prospective data in hand.` },
      { type: "p", text: `To completely de-risk the final signature, you must ensure your prospective data supports the Three Pillars of Capital Readiness. If all three pillars are solid, the capital expenditure is no longer a gamble; it is a mathematical certainty.` },

      { type: "figure", title: "Illustration 21: The Three Pillars of Capital Readiness", visual: "An architectural drawing of three heavy pillars— Demand Velocity , Margin Defensibility , and Operational Blueprint —holding up a massive steel roof labeled \"Capital Deployment.\"", caption: "Only deploy capital when the structure is complete." },

      { type: "h3", text: `Pillar 1: Demand Velocity (The Customer Signal is Locked)` },
      { type: "p", text: `You have proven that the customer wants the capability. But before you buy the machine, you must prove the velocity of that demand. A single PO for ten parts is a successful test, but it does not justify a ₹5 Crore automated cell.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The Capital Trigger: You commit capital only when the prospective data includes a contractual commitment to volume. This means the customer has signed a blanket order, an LOI for annual quantities, or has provided a binding 12-month forecast tied to your new capability. The machine must have guaranteed work waiting for it the moment it is bolted to your floor.` },

      { type: "h3", text: `Pillar 2: Margin Defensibility (The Math Works at Scale)` },
      { type: "p", text: `During the Thin-Slice experiment, you likely lost money because you brute-forced the production. That was your Cost of Learning. Now, you must project the true Cost of Production.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The Capital Trigger: You commit capital only when you have rigorously modeled the cycle times, tooling costs, and energy consumption of the new equipment, and the math proves that the premium price the customer just agreed to will yield a disproportionately high EBITDA margin. If the new machine only yields a 5% margin at the premium price, you do not buy it. The capital is only deployed if it creates a fortress of profitability.` },

      { type: "h3", text: `Pillar 3: The Operational Blueprint (We Know the Physics)` },
      { type: "p", text: `The testing phase exposed your internal operational weaknesses. When you ran the RFQ Stress Test, you discovered exactly where your current factory broke down. You found out your inspection department was too slow, or your tool crib was too disorganized.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The Capital Trigger: You commit capital only when you have a comprehensive blueprint for the Activity System required to support the new machine. You do not just buy the 5-axis mill; you authorize the budget for the new CAM software, the specialized cutting tools, and the climate-controlled QA room simultaneously. You fund the entire system, not just the centerpiece.` },

      { type: "h2", text: `Rapid-Fire Industry Translations: Scaling the Bet` },
      { type: "p", text: `Let us watch elite manufacturing teams seamlessly transition from cheap, scrappy market tests to massive, highly confident capital deployments across different sectors.` },

      { type: "h3", text: `The Heavy Iron Foundry` },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        "The Test: To test if the wind-energy sector would buy massive 15-ton single-piece castings from them, the foundry outsourced the creation of 3D-printed sand molds at a massive financial loss (The Proxy Test). The customer approved the casting quality and signed a 3-year supply agreement.",
        "The Capital Commitment: With the 3-year agreement locked (Pillar 1), the foundry immediately signs a ₹12 Crore loan to build a dedicated, fully automated massive-scale molding pit and a high-capacity induction furnace. The risk is zero. The 3-year agreement guarantees the EMI payments."
      ]},

      { type: "h3", text: `The Electronic Contract Manufacturer (EMS)` },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        "The Test: To test if medical startups would pay a premium for direct-to-end-user fulfillment, the EMS unit manually packed, labeled, and shipped a pilot batch of 500 devices using a spreadsheet and temporary labor (The Hack). The medical startup loved the service and signed a binding contract for 50,000 units a year.",
        "The Capital Commitment: Armed with the 50,000-unit contract, the EMS unit drops the spreadsheet and immediately deploys ₹1.5 Crore to implement an enterprise-grade Warehouse Management System (WMS), barcode scanners, and automated conveyor packaging lines. They scale the hack into a highly profitable, frictionless capability."
      ]},

      { type: "h3", text: `The Sheet Metal Stamping Plant` },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        "The Test: To test demand for a proprietary, deep-drawn EV battery casing, the plant created an Ugly Duckling by cutting flat sheets and TIG-welding the corners by hand. The EV manufacturer approved the weight and dimensions and issued an LOI for 200,000 units.",
        "The Capital Commitment: Because the LOI guarantees the volume, the stamping plant confidently writes a ₹80 Lakh cheque to a tool-and-die maker to cut the permanent, high-speed progressive steel stamping dies. They know the tooling cost will be amortized over the first 50,000 units, resulting in pure profit for the remaining 150,000."
      ]},

      { type: "h2", text: `Boardroom Facilitation: Staged Capital Deployment (Tranching)` },
      { type: "p", text: `Even with absolute confidence, signing a massive purchase order is a heavy psychological burden. As the CEO, you must manage your CFO’s natural anxiety during the execution phase.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The smartest way to deploy capital is not to buy ten years of capacity on Day One. The smartest way to scale is through Staged Capital Deployment, also known as Tranching.` },
      { type: "p", text: `You deploy just enough capital to eliminate the immediate bottleneck, and you hold the rest in reserve until the revenue physically hits the bank account.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Scenario: Your Fake Door test for a new line of automated commercial packaging machines was a massive success. You secured ₹5 Crore in pre-orders. Your Production Head bursts into the boardroom, thrilled.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The Production Head demands: "Boss, the demand is insane! We need to scale immediately. Let's lease the 20,000-square-foot facility next door, buy three new CNC machining centers to cut the frames, and hire twenty new assembly technicians today!"` },
      { type: "p", text: `The CFO panics: "Are you crazy? We only have a 10% deposit on those pre-orders! If we expand the facility and buy three machines, we will drain our entire working capital reserves. If even two of those buyers back out, we are bankrupt."` },
      { type: "p", text: `The Strategist’s Response (The Scientific Leader): "You are both right. The demand is proven, and we must execute flawlessly. But we are not going to over-leverage our balance sheet to do it. We will use Staged Deployment.\nTranche 1: We will NOT lease the building next door yet. We will reorganize our current warehouse to make room for one assembly line. We will buy ONE new CNC machining center today to handle the frame cutting. We will outsource the overflow cutting to our trusted vendor across town, even if it hurts our margin slightly.\nTranche 2: Once the first five packaging machines are delivered, installed, and the customers pay the final 90% invoice, we will take that pure cash flow and trigger Tranche 2. We will buy the second CNC machine and hire the remaining technicians.\nWe scale the capital exactly in step with the realized cash flow. We never let our fixed costs outrun our prospective data."` },
      { type: "p", text: `By forcing the team to tranche the capital, you protect the company from "success disasters"—where a company grows so fast that it runs out of cash to buy raw materials. You ensure the strategy remains financially bulletproof at every stage of execution.` },

      { type: "figure", title: "Illustration 22: Staged Capital Deployment (Tranching)", visual: "A stair-step graph showing capital expenditure incrementally stepping up only after realized cash flow steps up, preventing 'success disasters.'", caption: "Do not let your fixed costs outrun your prospective data." },

      { type: "p", text: `The Founder Pushback: The "Perpetual Pivot"\nWhile some founders rush into capital traps, a rare but equally dangerous breed of founder suffers from the opposite problem. Once they discover the power and safety of Thin-Slicing, they become addicted to testing. They become terrified of commitment.\nHere are the two excuses founders use to delay capital deployment after the strategy has been validated, and the brutal truth behind them.` },

      { type: "figure", title: "Illustration 23: Escaping the Perpetual Pivot", visual: "A decision tree showing how to stop addicted testers from running redundant experiments when the 85% confidence metric has already been achieved.", caption: "Testing is not an excuse for cowardice." },

      { type: "pushback", 
        myth: `“The RFQ Stress Test was a success, but what if it was just a fluke? What if that specific buyer was just desperate that week? We should run five more experiments over the next six months just to be absolutely sure before we buy the machine.”`, 
        truth: `This is called the Perpetual Pivot. You are using "testing" as an excuse for cowardice. The market gave you the signal. If you delay execution to run endless redundant tests, your competitor will notice the gap in the market, buy the machine, and steal your premium buyers.`, 
        shift: `Absolute, 100% certainty does not exist in business. Testing gets you to 85% confidence. The remaining 15% requires executive courage. When the data hits the metric, you must pull the trigger.` 
      },
      { type: "pushback", 
        myth: `“We secured the LOI using the Ugly Duckling prototype. But instead of spending the capital on the permanent tooling now, let's just keep hacking it together manually for the first year to save money.”`, 
        truth: `A hack is designed to generate data, not to fulfill mass production. If you try to run a ₹50 Crore contract using manual workarounds and overtime, your operators will burn out, your quality will collapse, and you will miss your delivery dates. The customer will fire you for incompetence.`, 
        shift: `The Cost of Learning is meant to be temporary. Once the market proves the demand, you must instantly switch to optimizing the Cost of Production. You must buy the efficient capability, or you will destroy your own reputation.` 
      },

      { type: "worksheet", 
        id: "ws-capital-release",
        title: "Worksheet Audit: The Capital Release Valve",
        description: "This is the final boardroom checkpoint. You do not sign the purchase order, the commercial lease, or the bank loan until your executive team can unanimously check every box on this list.",
        questions: [
          `1. The Deal Killer is Dead: We ran a specific market experiment, and the prospective data definitively neutralized our scariest assumption.`,
          `2. The Volume is Contracted: We have a signed PO, LOI, or binding forecast that guarantees enough immediate volume to cover the first 12 months of the machine's EMI.`,
          `3. The Margin is Defensible: Our internal cost modeling proves that running this new capability at scale will generate a premium EBITDA margin, not just revenue.`,
          `4. The System is Funded: We are not just buying a machine; we have allocated the budget for the software, tooling, and training required to actually run it.`,
          `5. The Deployment is Tranched: We are buying only the capacity required to clear the immediate bottleneck, holding further capital in reserve until cash flow is realized.`
        ]
      },
      { type: "p", text: `The Diagnosis:\nIf any box remains unchecked, put your pen down. You are not ready to commit the capital. Go back to the market, generate more prospective data, or restructure your financing.\nBut if every box is checked, the time for hesitation is over.\nYou have done what 95% of manufacturing companies never do. You designed a brilliant strategy, you ruthlessly isolated its weaknesses, and you proved it in the real world without risking your balance sheet. You have built a machine of pure, calculated confidence.\nSign the cheque. Buy the machine. Dominate the arena.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "final",
    title: "Final Chapter: Building a Strategic Learning Habit",
    type: "chapter",
    blocks: [
      { type: "h1", text: `Final Chapter\nBuilding a Strategic Learning Habit` },
      { type: "p", text: `You have experienced the adrenaline of a successful strategic test.` },
      { type: "p", text: `You isolated a terrifying Deal Killer assumption. You designed a brilliant Thin-Slice experiment. You generated undeniable prospective data. You watched the customer sign the Letter of Intent, validating your pricing power and your How to Win before you ever called the bank. You deployed your capital with absolute, mathematical confidence.` },
      { type: "p", text: `It feels like a massive victory. And it is.` },
      { type: "p", text: `But at this exact moment, mid-sized manufacturing companies face their final and most insidious trap.` },
      { type: "p", text: `They treat strategic testing as a one-time event.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Because the test was successful, the leadership team high-fives each other, buys the new machines, and immediately reverts to their old operational habits. They put their heads down, focus entirely on production efficiency, and stop looking at the horizon. They stop testing.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Five years later, the market shifts. A new competitor enters the arena with a cheaper, faster capability. The once-brilliant strategy becomes a commodity. Because the leadership team lost their testing muscle, they panic, rely on a "gut feeling," and blindly bet the business on a desperate, untested capital expenditure.` },
      { type: "p", text: `They fall right back into the Capital Trap.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Great manufacturing companies do not rely on one big, lucky decision. They do not view strategy as a document they update every three years. They view strategy as a living, breathing, continuous process. They build a culture where generating prospective data is just as important as generating daily production output.` },
      { type: "p", text: `You must transition your company from running a "testing project" to building a Strategic Learning Habit.` },

      { type: "h2", text: `Micro-Teardown: The Monthly Strategy Review vs. The Operations Review` },
      { type: "p", text: `To build a permanent testing habit, you must fundamentally change the cadence of your boardroom meetings.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Almost every manufacturing company holds a Monthly Operations Review. The executives sit around a table and look at lagging indicators. They look at machine utilization (OEE), scrap rates, overtime hours, and late shipments. The Production Manager explains why a machine broke down, and the VP of Sales explains why they missed their quota.` },
      { type: "p", text: `An Operations Review is completely focused on the past and the present. It optimizes the Cost of Production.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Elite companies hold a secondary meeting: The Monthly Strategic Learning Review. This meeting is completely focused on the future. In this room, you are not allowed to talk about yesterday's late shipment. You are only allowed to talk about tomorrow's Deal Killers. You are optimizing the Cost of Learning.` },
      { type: "p", text: `In the Strategic Learning Review, the leadership team actively hunts for new assumptions. As the market shifts, what new risks are appearing in the Customer, Competitor, or Company buckets? What new premium capabilities could we offer? What proxy prototypes do we need to build this month to test a new pricing tier?` },
      { type: "p", text: `By forcing this meeting onto the calendar every single month, you institutionalize the scientific method. You train your managers that their job is not just to run the factory, but to continuously probe the edges of the market for the next massive advantage.` },
      
      { type: "figure", title: "Illustration 24: The Monthly Strategic Learning Review vs. Operations Review", visual: "A split-screen visual. One side shows managers looking backward at last month's scrap rates; the other side shows executives looking forward at next month's Deal Killers.", caption: "Optimize for learning as aggressively as you optimize for production." },

      { type: "h2", text: `Rapid-Fire Industry Translations: The Habit in Action` },
      { type: "p", text: `Let us look at how elite manufacturers embed continuous strategic testing into their daily operations, ensuring they never deploy capital blindly again.` },

      { type: "h3", text: `The Injection Molding Plant` },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        "The Old Habit: Waiting for a customer to request a new biodegradable resin, then buying a massive 10-ton silo of the material to run a production test.",
        "The Learning Habit: Every quarter, the engineering team is given a ₹50,000 \"Cost of Learning\" budget. They buy tiny, 20kg sample bags of experimental aerospace-grade or biodegradable resins. They run them through a small test press during the night shift just to learn the melting temperatures and cycle times. When a customer finally asks for that specific capability, the molder already possesses the prospective data. They quote the job instantly with absolute confidence, while competitors spend weeks trying to figure out the physics."
      ]},

      { type: "h3", text: `The Sheet Metal Fabrication Shop` },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        "The Old Habit: The sales team blindly quotes standard commercial jobs all day, fighting over pennies.",
        "The Learning Habit: The VP of Sales institutes the \"One-in-Ten Rule.\" For every ten standard quotes sent out, the sales team must deliberately send one \"RFQ Stress Test.\" They take a standard RFQ and quote a massive premium in exchange for a radical new value proposition (like Vendor Managed Inventory or 24-hour turnaround). They expect 9 out of 10 stress tests to be rejected. But they are constantly generating prospective data on the ceiling of their pricing power, actively hunting for the exact moment the market is willing to pay more."
      ]},

      { type: "h3", text: `The Custom Cable Assembly Unit` },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        "The Old Habit: Spending ₹5 Lakhs redesigning their website every three years based on what the marketing agency thinks looks \"modern.\"",
        "The Learning Habit: The marketing team runs continuous Fake Door tests. They build hidden landing pages for high-end, specialized medical cable assemblies they do not currently manufacture. They spend ₹5,000 a month on LinkedIn ads targeting medical procurement officers to see if anyone clicks \"Request a Sample.\" They monitor the digital foot traffic. They use cheap digital real estate to test massive physical capital decisions."
      ]},

      { type: "h2", text: `Boardroom Facilitation: The CEO as the Chief Architect of Confidence` },
      { type: "p", text: `When you attempt to institutionalize the Strategic Learning Habit, your team will resist. They will claim they are too busy putting out operational fires to run Fake Door tests or build Ugly Ducklings.` },
      { type: "p", text: `As the CEO, your final transformation is to become the absolute enforcer of prospective data. You must ruthlessly defend the testing budget and the testing timeline.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Scenario: During your Monthly Strategic Learning Review, your Head of Product Development pitches a brilliant idea to create a proprietary, IoT-enabled industrial sensor housing. He asks for a ₹25 Lakh budget to build the initial injection molds so he can take samples to a trade show next quarter.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The Wrong Response (The Reverting CEO): "I love the idea. It sounds like the future. The budget is approved. Get the molds cut in time for the show."\n(Why this is wrong: You just reverted to the Capital Trap. You approved a massive capital expenditure based on a pitch, not a test.)` },
      { type: "p", text: `The Right Response (The Scientific Leader): "The concept is brilliant, and if the market wants it, we will dominate that trade show. But you are asking for ₹25 Lakhs of capital without a shred of prospective data. What is the Deal Killer assumption here? The assumption is that factory managers actually want to pay a premium for IoT housings instead of standard dumb housings.\nI am not approving the ₹25 Lakh mold budget today. I am approving a ₹50,000 learning budget. Your job for the next 14 days is to 3D-print five hyper-realistic visual models of this housing, glue a fake LED light to them, take them to five of our best clients, and ask them to sign a pre-order LOI. If you bring me three signed LOIs by the 15th of the month, the ₹25 Lakh mold budget is yours. Do not build the product until you have proven the demand."` },
      { type: "p", text: `By using this exact script, you never kill innovation. You simply force innovation to earn its capital through rigor, discipline, and undeniable prospective data.` },

      { type: "worksheet", 
        id: "ws-learning-dashboard",
        title: "Worksheet Audit: The Strategic Learning Dashboard",
        description: "To ensure your company never falls back into the Capital Trap, you must track your tests just as rigorously as you track your inventory. Draw this dashboard on a massive whiteboard in your boardroom. It must be visible to every executive, every day.",
        questions: [
          `1. Active Strategic Hypothesis 1 | The Deal Killer Assumption | The Thin-Slice Experiment | Cost of Learning Budget | Deadline | The Verdict (Kill/Pivot/Persevere)`,
          `2. Active Strategic Hypothesis 2 | The Deal Killer Assumption | The Thin-Slice Experiment | Cost of Learning Budget | Deadline | The Verdict (Kill/Pivot/Persevere)`,
          `3. Active Strategic Hypothesis 3 | The Deal Killer Assumption | The Thin-Slice Experiment | Cost of Learning Budget | Deadline | The Verdict (Kill/Pivot/Persevere)`
        ]
      },
      { type: "p", text: `The Diagnosis:\nLook at your dashboard. If the board is empty, your company is coasting. You are living off the fumes of your past strategic decisions, and you are completely blind to the future.\nA healthy, aggressive manufacturing company should always have two or three active experiments running in the background. You should be constantly failing small, cheap tests so you never fail a massive, expensive one.\nWhen your leadership team learns to embrace the friction of testing, the fear of capital expenditure completely vanishes. You stop guessing. You stop arguing. You stop relying on the polite lies of corporate buyers.\nYou build a machine that converts ambiguity into certainty.` },
      { type: "p", text: `You have learned how to test your strategy. You have protected your business from catastrophic bets. But testing alone is not enough to build an empire.\nTesting a weak, generic strategy just proves that the strategy is weak, slightly faster. To truly dominate your industry, you must combine the ruthless testing logic of this book with a master-level blueprint for market domination.\nYou must integrate your Where to Play, your How to Win, your capital deployment, and your operational management systems into one unified, unstoppable force.\nIt is time to build the ultimate machine.` },

      { type: "h2", text: `Next: The Integrated Strategy Manual\nThe ₹100 Cr Decision Factory` },
      { type: "p", text: `Strategy in Action for Manufacturing Businesses\nYou now know how to stop writing Laudable Lists (Book 1). You know the fatal difference between operational planning and strategic choice (Book 2). And you now possess the elite capability to slice your most terrifying assumptions into cheap, rapid experiments, generating the prospective data required to deploy capital safely (Book 3).` },
      { type: "p", text: `But how do you bring all of these distinct weapons together into a single, cohesive operational system?\nIn the massive, final volume of this series— The ₹100 Cr Decision Factory —we move from theory and testing to absolute, scaled execution. This is the comprehensive, integrated strategy manual for the mid-sized manufacturer.` },
      { type: "p", text: `In that definitive book, you will see exactly how real-world, highly profitable companies:\nChoose where to compete: How to mathematically analyze a market arena and identify the unprotected flanks of massive, billion-dollar competitors.\nBuild structural advantages: How to design an Activity System so complex and deeply integrated that your rivals cannot possibly copy it, even if they buy the exact same machines.\nDevelop proprietary capabilities: How to align your tool cribs, your quality departments, and your HR hiring profiles to perfectly support your specific How to Win.\nScale strategically: How to structure your executive team, build the KPIs, and manage the daily cadence required to drive a high-margin strategy past the ₹100 Crore mark without losing your agility.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Through highly detailed, multi-chapter case studies and advanced strategy design tools, The ₹100 Cr Decision Factory is the ultimate blueprint for turning a chaotic job shop into a highly focused, premium-margin market leader.\nYou have stopped planning. You have stopped betting the business on hope.\nNow, it is time to build the factory that makes the decisions.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id: "appendix-a",
    title: "Appendix A: Comprehensive Bibliography & References",
    type: "chapter",
    blocks: [
      { type: "h1", text: `Appendix A\nComprehensive Bibliography & References` },
      { type: "p", text: `The testing methodologies, risk-mitigation frameworks, and behavioral diagnostic tools presented in Don’t Bet the Business synthesize decades of peer-reviewed research in corporate strategy, B2B procurement psychology, behavioral economics, and Lean/Agile industrial deployment.` },
      { type: "p", text: `The core architectural concepts of this book—specifically the WWHTBT framework, the Fake Door (Pretotyping) test, and the decoupling of the Cost of Learning from the Cost of Production—are deeply indebted to the foundational academic work of Roger L. Martin, Rita Gunther McGrath, Alberto Savoia, and Daniel Kahneman.` },
      { type: "p", text: `For founders, CFOs, and leadership teams who require the empirical and academic foundations of this methodology before deploying it in their boardrooms, the following texts and papers form the bedrock of our approach.` },
      
      { type: "h2", text: `I. Strategy as Hypothesis & Assumption Testing` },
      { type: "p", text: `(The theoretical foundation for WWHTBT, Thin-Slicing, and validating strategic logic before capital deployment).` },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        "Lafley, A. G., & Martin, R. L. (2013). Playing to Win: How Strategy Really Works. Harvard Business Review Press. (The definitive source for the \"What Would Have to Be True?\" framework).",
        "McGrath, R. G., & MacMillan, I. C. (1995). \"Discovery-Driven Planning.\" Harvard Business Review. (The foundational paper on planning for untested assumptions).",
        "McGrath, R. G. (2013). The End of Competitive Advantage: How to Keep Your Strategy Moving as Fast as Your Business. Harvard Business Review Press.",
        "Savoia, A. (2019). The Right It: Why So Many Ideas Fail and How to Make Sure Yours Succeed. HarperOne. (The academic origin of \"Pretotyping\" and the \"Fake Door\" test).",
        "Blank, S. (2013). \"Why the Lean Start-Up Changes Everything.\" Harvard Business Review.",
        "Blank, S., & Dorf, B. (2012). The Startup Owner's Manual: The Step-by-Step Guide for Building a Great Company. K&S Ranch.",
        "Ries, E. (2011). The Lean Startup: How Today's Entrepreneurs Use Continuous Innovation to Create Radically Successful Businesses. Crown Business.",
        "Thomke, S. H. (2020). Experimentation Works: The Surprising Power of Business Experiments. Harvard Business Review Press.",
        "Thomke, S. H. (2003). Experimentation Matters: Unlocking the Potential of New Technologies for Innovation. Harvard Business School Press.",
        "Osterwalder, A., Pigneur, Y., Bernarda, G., & Smith, A. (2014). Value Proposition Design: How to Create Products and Services Customers Want. Wiley.",
        "Maurya, A. (2012). Running Lean: Iterate from Plan A to a Plan That Works. O'Reilly Media.",
        "Furr, N., & Dyer, J. (2014). The Innovator's Method: Bringing the Lean Start-up into Your Organization. Harvard Business Review Press.",
        "Mullins, J. W. (2006). The New Business Road Test: What Entrepreneurs and Executives Should Do Before Writing a Business Plan. Financial Times Press.",
        "Brown, T. (2008). \"Design Thinking.\" Harvard Business Review.",
        "Martin, R. L. (2009). The Design of Business: Why Design Thinking is the Next Competitive Advantage. Harvard Business Press."
